### Description

Today one can run `ng test` to run tests across all projects with a configured `test` builder, or `ng test <project>` to run tests in a single project. However if the monorepo contains projects with both jest and karma tests it gets pretty clunky to run both. 

As Angular moves toward multiple test builders there should be support for running all tests globally for select types of tests.

### Describe the solution you'd like

Ideally `ng test` would run all tests across all projects using all configured test builders, and it would be possible to configure multiple test builders for a single project. And then it would be possible to only run tests for a single test builder using a property, like `ng test --runner=karma`, where the runner value is defined by the builder.

### Describe alternatives you've considered

The following can be added to angular.json for each project:
```json
"projects": {
    "mylib": {
      "projectType": "library",
      "root": "projects/mylib",
      "sourceRoot": "projects/mylib/src",
      "prefix": "lib",
      "architect": {
        "build": {
...
        },
        "test-karma": {
          "builder": "@angular-devkit/build-angular:karma",
          "options": {
            "tsConfig": "projects/mylib/tsconfig.karma-spec.json",
            "polyfills": [
              "zone.js",
              "zone.js/testing"
            ],
            "include": [
              "**/*.karma-spec.ts"
            ],
            "codeCoverageExclude": [
              "**/*.jest-spec.ts"
            ]
          }
        },
        "test-jest": {
          "builder": "@angular-devkit/build-angular:jest",
          "options": {
            "tsConfig": "tsconfig.jest-spec.json",
            "polyfills": [
              "zone.js",
              "zone.js/testing"
            ],
            "include": [
              "**/*.jest-spec.ts"
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    },
```

Such a configuration supports 2 test builders for the project, so `ng mylib:test-karma` and `ng mylib:test-jest` works, but I can no longer `ng test` to run all tests in the workspace. Of course I could avoid leave one of the builder using `test` in all my projects, but it is still a limitation. 

The current lines in my package.json would have to be updated for each new project. The following is required for only 2 projects, and it would get unwieldy for 15-20 projects:

```json
  "scripts": {
    "test:karma": "ng run mylib:test-karma --watch false && ng run myapp:test-karma --watch false",
    "test:jest": "NODE_NO_WARNINGS=1 ng run mylib:test-jest && NODE_NO_WARNINGS=1 ng run myapp:test-jest"
```

This project (checkout the `dev/jest` branch) provides an example:
https://github.com/johncrim/ng16-yarn-pnp/tree/dev/jest

(Note also that running `yarn test:jest` runs all the jest tests 2x, presumably because the `tsconfig.jest-spec.json` references test files from multiple projects. Obviously this can be fixed with tsconfig files in each project)

